  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2653368363" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2653368363" />
    <a title="Laurie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/61555947-laurie"><img alt="Laurie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479168451p2/61555947.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2653368363?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laurie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laurie" href="/user/show/61555947-laurie">Laurie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61555947-laurie?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/61555947-laurie?shelf=read-my-library-challenge">read-my-library-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2653368363" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13641995159307149348">It took me a while to get into his writing style, but once I did I really enjoyed the book. While I didn&apos;t always agree with the things he said, I appreciated being immersed in his very distinctive and unique perspective. However, the reason I kept reading wasn&apos;t for the writing--be aware he wanders and often repeats himself--but for the unfolding of the events at the moment of the Mann Gulch tragedy. <br/><br/>Part Two was my favorite section of the book, and it is worth it to push yourself to get throug</span>
  <span id="freeText13641995159307149348" style="display:none">It took me a while to get into his writing style, but once I did I really enjoyed the book. While I didn't always agree with the things he said, I appreciated being immersed in his very distinctive and unique perspective. However, the reason I kept reading wasn't for the writing--be aware he wanders and often repeats himself--but for the unfolding of the events at the moment of the Mann Gulch tragedy. <br /><br />Part Two was my favorite section of the book, and it is worth it to push yourself to get through it. There is a chart at the end that shows how quickly the men and fire were moving, and even without reading the explanations, you can see as the times and distances close that the men had very little chance of escaping the final conflagration.<br /><br />Part Three was disappointing and left a bitter residue at the conclusion of the book. Instead of reflecting on the answers MacLean found regarding the events that occurred in the fire, he goes into a flight of fancy in this last section. The descriptions of the fire are bizarre here: "The vast wildfire continued on its bi-visual way--mushroom impregnated by a snake in the grass and sometimes like gray brains boiling out of the crevice of the earth. Then the brains themselves became bi-visual and changed again into suffering gray intestines." Maybe it's just me, but I can't picture this in any way that connects with reality. <br /><br />On top of this, he puts words and thoughts into the heads of the young men that contradict everything he'd said earlier in the book. It is clear that rather than being their thoughts, it is his perspective on it. He says the two living survivors told him they remember thinking only, "My God, how could you do this to me? I cannot be allowed to die so young and so close to the top." But in Part One, he says the survivors said they weren't panicked, and Rumsey said, "I kept thinking the ridge--if I can make it. On the ridge I will be safe. . . " And MacLean frequently repeats in Part One that this is the only thought Rumsey had--his singular focus on reaching the top of the ridge.<br /><br />So rather than the book ending strong, with a deeper meaning or understanding of the tragic events, it ended with a whimper. I'm still rating the book with 5 stars, because I learned so much about the Mann Gulch fire. But I wish the book had ended with Part Two.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13641995159307149348" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

